m, this was an exceptionally turbulent time in the history of industrial capitalism as Taylorism and Fordism sought to increase production and consumption. This social landscape shaped modernist industrial novels. Key themes in these novels were class conflict, bad working conditions, worker alienation, changing workmen and employee cultures, urbanization, and worker migration. The primary goal was to document and publicize the real developments of working conditions in factories and offices, often aiming to influence both company welfare work and state social policies. This book focuses on the modernist industrial novel as written in five large industrial nations: the United States before WWII, the Stalinist Soviet Union, Weimar Germany, post-WWII Italy, and France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndustries in literature. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aModern History. 4aSOC. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aModernist Industrial novels, industrial sociology, Americanization, worker alienation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048552399?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048552399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048552399/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles